aracters define the hierarchy as they're encountered. I'm realizing that in reStructuredText, once a character is assigned to a heading level, it maintains that level throughout the document—so the `-` underlines should all be h2, and the `=` underlines should all be h3, regardless of how many characters are used. Let me re-examine the actual section structure to verify this pattern holds consistently. Looking at the structure more carefully, I see the document breaks down into sections with varying heading levels marked by dashes. The knowledge file captures 8 sections total, which seems to cover the main content areas. Now I'm checking the character counts for each section to see if they're appropriately sized — s2 comes in at only 40 characters, which is notably short compared to the others, but the rest appear to have adequate length.\n\nI'm also reviewing the hints in section 7 to verify that class names and annotations are properly captured. The hints include a good range of technical references like ValidationUtil, W11AC03Form, and various utility classes, though I should check if there are any missing pieces in the annotation coverage. I'm noticing that `doRW11AC0301` is an action method name from the source that isn't covered in the hints, which could be important to include. I'm also seeing that the knowledge files use RST syntax for download links like `:download:`W11AC03Action.java<...>`` — this syntax won't translate well to markdown or JSON format, though it might be worth preserving as-is to maintain the file references.\n\nLooking at the key issues: section s2 is quite short at around 38 characters, and in s7 there's a `getWindowScopeObject` private method that's omitted from the code example, though since its body is abbreviated and it's called within the included method, this seems acceptable for an AI assistant context. The `getWindowScopeObject` method is missing from the knowledge file entirely—it constructs and returns a form object populated w